The frames containing the artificially-infested brood cells were placed in a chamber with controlled conditions of temperature and humidity (35 ± 1 °C and 60 ± 2%, respectively) for eleven days ( Figure 1 ). Next, the capped brood cells were carefully opened with a scalpel, and the foundress and the presumably sexually mature daughters were collected. The daughter (F1) and foundress (P) mites were identified by their pigmentation (
Rosenkranz et al. , 2010
). Once identified, female mites were separated, immediately mounted on nurse bees obtained from LL colony brood frames, and placed in glass flasks (3L) ( Figure 1 ). Each glass flask of P or F1 mites harbored thirty nurse bees and ten mites. The flasks were provided with containers with honey and water ad libitum and placed in a chamber with controlled conditions of temperature and humidity (35 ± 1 °C and 60%, respectively) in darkness for 4 days (Figure

